posts.title: Berlin: First Sunday in Advent
posts.text:
Berlin, Germany Latitude 52 ˚ 52 N December 4, 2017 
For years I’ve been hearing Berlin stories: Alexanderplatz, Brandenburg Gate, Potstam, Checkpoint Charlie…   It was finally time for me to take the plunge and see the place for myself.   And what better time, in my limited world view, than Christmas. 
Christmas.   “Be careful, Dan.”   I heard that a lot.   And I know people are well-meaning.   A year ago some lunatic drove a vehicle into a Christmas market and killed who knows how many people.   But I refuse, absolutely refuse, to give in to fears.   Maybe it will happen again.   Maybe it will happen in Nuremburg.   Maybe in Mexico City.   I could get killed on the way home from the airport when I return home.   No.   I won’t give in. 
From all I’d read about Berlin in the 1930’s, I expected some wild town, with crazy things happening all around me.   What I found, instead, was a sedate city, brand new since the 1960’s and rather, well…boring.   I should not be harsh.   The city was essentially a pile of rubble at the end of WW 2.   What it was, however, was a very walkable city.   Once I oriented myself I realized that just about everything was on a straight-line axis.   Fortunately, the weather was fine and not as cold as Riga or Vilnius, so my feet brought me just about everywhere.   One day I clocked 27,000 steps on my pedometer and the next day I just could not replicate the march from the day before.   I’d walked from Alexanderplatz to Charlottenburg—a distance of maybe 6 or 7 miles.   My quest for hitting every Christmas market in the city knew no bounds.   But my exhaustion did, and on day three I just collapsed and was back in my room by 5:00 pm.    There are limits to what the tourist body can do. 
On my last day there I headed to Potstam.   It was time to the leave the city and this seemed a good destination.   It was also personal, as my sister lives in Potstam, NY, not that the two have anything in common.   Oh, such perfection.   I found my way to the first Christmas market, a much tamer affair than those in Berlin, and just as I began walking it started to snow—Light, mysterious, and delicate.   A cool, dry fragrance was released into the air.   It snowed just enough to say it was snowing.   Snowing!   At a German Christmas market.   I was ecstatic.   My secondary goal in Potstam was San Soucci gardens, a massive park very close to the center.   That strange chemistry of snow and nostalgia took possession.   For a time, I was on Rand Hill, more than forty years ago, on the first full day of winter—a days of cold and dark and snow—cross country skiing into the darkening woods.   It was twilight and it snowed the entire time I was walking in this park, which felt more like a forest than anything else.   

When I returned to the Christmas market I’d been at a few hours earlier I walked through the cold, snow-filled street.   An hour later I was back on the train to Berlin.   It was an absolutely perfect day.

(AP) — A white former South Carolina officer was sentenced to 20 years in prison on Thursday for fatally shooting an unarmed black motorist in the back in 2015, wrapping up a case that became a rallying cry for the Black Lives Matter movement.
Attorneys for ex-North Charleston Officer Michael Slager said he shot 50-year-old Walter Scott in self-defense after the two fought and Scott grabbed Slager's stun gun. They said race didn't play a role in the shooting and Slager never had any "racial animus" toward minorities.
Still, Slager pleaded guilty in federal court to violating Scott's civil rights. As part of the plea agreement reached in May, prosecutors dropped state murder charges. A year ago, a state judge declared a mistrial when jurors deadlocked in that case.
Now Playing: The sentencing hearing for the form South Carolina police officer who shot and killed an unarmed black man in 2015 begins Monday. Josh King has the story (@abridgeotland).
Media: Veuer "This is a tragedy that shouldn't have happened," U.S. District Judge David Norton said.
A bystander recorded the shooting on a cellphone, and it was shared around the world, setting off protests across the U.S. as demonstrators said it was another egregious example of police officers mistreating African-Americans.
Scott's family testified before the sentence was handed down and said they had forgiven Slager.
Related Stories The Latest: Ex-cop's attorney asks for minimum sentence Son of slain black man wants life in prison for ex-officer Evidence a little different at ex-officer's sentencing "I'm not angry at you, Michael. Michael, I forgive you, and Michael, I do pray for you now and for your family, because we've gone through a traumatic time," said Scott's brother Anthony.
The shooting angered local African-Americans who complained for years that North Charleston police harassed blacks, pulling them over or questioning them unnecessarily as they cracked down on crime. But after the shooting, the Scott family successfully pleaded for calm, asking everyone to let the justice system run its course.
Two months after the shooting, a young white man killed nine black church members in a racially motivated attacked during a Bible study in Charleston. The family members of those victims struck a similar forgiveness tone after that attack.
Before the sentence was handed down, the judge had to decide whether the shooting amounted to second-degree murder or manslaughter. Norton found that it was murder.
"No matter what sentence I give, neither the Scott family nor the Slager family is going to think that it's right," the judge said.
The bystander's video started after the struggle between Slager and Scott and showed Scott running away and the officer firing eight times. Scott was hit in the back five times.
After the shooting, Slager picked up his stun gun and placed it next to Scott. Slager contends he was securing the weapon. Prosecutors think he put it there to bolster his self-defense story.
An emotional Slager told the Scott family that he was grateful for their forgiveness.
"This tragic event that occurred in seconds has changed the lives of everyone involved," he said. "With my actions that day, Walter Scott is no longer with his family, and I am responsible for that."
The judge also found that Slager, 36, obstructed justice when he made statements to state police after the shooting.
A pre-sentencing report for Slager found that he committed manslaughter and recommended 10 to nearly 13 years in prison. But the judge was not bound by that review.
If Slager had faced another state trial and been convicted of murder, he could have been sentenced to anywhere from 30 years to life in prison.
Convictions in police officer shootings are uncommon in the U.S. and prison time is even rarer.
South Carolina has been aggressive in charging white officers who shoot unarmed black people. Four have pleaded guilty in state or federal court in the past six years. But only Slager and former state trooper Sean Groubert, who shot a man as he tried to get his wallet during a seat belt violation check, will have been sent to prison. Groubert was sentenced to five years behind bars.

posts.author: Oodly
posts.title: Confusing motor failure
posts.text:
So this happened... a 15 HP, 3 phase, 460v motor stopped working. Its VFD refused to run and would go into overcurrent alarm before delivering any voltage to the motor. I confirmed I had 3 legs of power, all good. Wanting to eliminate the motor as the problem I megged it and read infinity GOHMS to ground. Resistance readings between phases were equal at .9 ohms. Another tech was there who also had a megger on his truck. We repeated the test with his gear and got all the same readings. This was a motor that had been in service, but we checked the make-up of its leads anyway, all were correct. So we bypassed the VFD and wired the motor across the line. I turned power on as the other tech observed the motor in the other room... he said it instantly popped loudly and lightning came out of it.
So what happened? Did we miss some steps in evaluating the motor? The short took out a leg of power in a non re-settable current limiter in the breaker, we've since replaced that. We obviously need a new motor, but I don't really want to go further without understanding what went wrong.
Thanks.

posts.author: BennyD
posts.text:
Do you have a low ohm meter? It's very hard to read the winding resistance. You should have a minimum of 1k ohms per volt when performing a Meg test to ground. Between legs is usually less than an ohm. You didn't do anything wrong. Leg to leg is just hard to read if you don't have the right equipment.
Another thought... If you have a battery powered phase rotation meter, they can usually tell motor rotation by spinning the motor by hand. It may give you a goofy reading if there is a short between windings. I've never tried it though...

>50
The first, and possibly only thing on your mind; where's Fayne, as you ask as much to the other.
"Why, I'm right here! My dear Husband, art thou having a lapse of the mind?"
The other speaks in a disturbing manner, as you try to get a better impression. Those strange eyes, that large bare head, and four tendril appendages from the face (what had been wrapped about your head), all about a foul maw. Where from the smell and taste came, locked in an kiss of dark passion as you were with that horrific, rank mouth to your own and grasping tentacles wrapped across your face.
An adventurer you were, though not a particularly great one. You did your small bit and got out while you were ahead, never really a profession. But you did hear tales, legends of things that dwell below and beyond. Of baleful monsters that prey on the mind, whose motives are unknowable. Just stories you thought, but lest you've lost your mind, here you are faced with one. In a panic you start to evaluate the situation, actually feeling like retching now when you look down to remember as well as feel, that you're still joined as lovers. Hastily you struggle to withdraw from nether this foul thing, a contented sigh from the thing when finally you pull free yourself from below, so to speak. The rest of your body is still caught in embrace though, the feel of the clammy larger figure laying atop your own and holding onto you as your beloved had. Sickened, you let your hands free from gripping the "goods" so to speak as they had been, and try to pry yourself out of that horrific embrace. The other though, doesn't want to let go and frighteningly seems stronger than you are, by enough at least. Seemingly comfortable, or even enjoying the snugness.
"Whatever is the matter, my love? You're not straying anywhere, are you? You seems't so eager to continue not moments ago."
Your survivor instincts start to kick into gear as you try to think of a way out, but every physical action take to further free yourself seems prevented by the being, a move of the body against yours here, an altered grip of the hand to yours there, almost like it has the sense to halt your intended actions before you have a chance to fully make them. Your panic increases till finally you're ready to snap and just fight tooth and nail for your life to break free, until all other emotions turn to ash in one dreaded moment, and only despair remains;
Naked as you are is the creature, but there on it's wrist plain to see is the marriage token bracelet given to your beloved, a perfect fit.

posts.text:
Round here the family reminisce fondly about the old days when we used to feed all the cows with small bales with gangs of happy local youths spending the warm summer days helping us get the loads in, and the myth has grown up that all the summer workers went with the arrival of the RP12 round baler and 4wd loader, which revolutionised life on our family dairy farm in 1990. There is always a certain amount of niggle about it.
What actually happened, though, was that by 1990 it was becoming impossible to find anyone who would reliably come to help as no=one wanted the work, even with generous wages. This has now been forgotten in the local mythology.
In this case, the new technology was introduced reluctantly as a result of fewer helpers, it didn't drive them away, but once it was here I never looked back!

thread.title: Why I dragged Resident Doctors to court – Enugu lawyer
thread.title_full: Why I dragged Resident Doctors to court – Enugu lawyer

posts.author: Ayobami Blog (noreply@blogger.com)
posts.title: Why I dragged Resident Doctors to court – Enugu lawyer
posts.text:
The National Association of Resident Doctors of Nigeria (NARD) has been dragged to court by an Enugu-based lawyer, Barr. Ikechukwu Maximus Ugwuoke. 

The writ for summary judgment filed at the Enugu State High Court in Suit No E/767/2017, borders on what Ugwuoke claimed was deliberate refusal, failure and neglect of the doctors to keep to terms of their agreement with his law firm. 


He claimed in the suit that he was at the moment handling over 11 cases involving the association. 
The suit has the said lawyer as plaintiff carrying on legal practice in the name and style of El-Maximus Ugwuoke & Co, Hakuna Matata Chambers. 
Defendants in the suit include the National Association of Resident Doctors, NARD, sued through Dr. Ugochukwu Chinaka and Dr. O.V Nnadi, the current President and Secretary of the Association as the 1st and 2nd Defendants respectively, while Dr. Onyebueze John Ugochukwu and Dr. Aneke Emmanuel, the Immediate Past President and Secretary of the Association were listed as the 3rd and 4th defendants, respectively. 
In the said suit obtained by DAILY POST, the lawyer is seeking an Order of Court compelling the Defendants to pay him the sum of N18, 450,000 (Eighteen Million Four hundred and Fifty thousand naira) only, “being the outstanding legal fee which the defendants are owing the Plaintiff’s law firm for the 11 cases they were briefed to handle for the Defendants pursuant to clause 5(ii) the memorandum of understanding between the said Law firm and the Association.” 

Ugwuoke told journalists that he had discharged his obligation under clause 5 (ii) of the said MOU which entitles his firm to the fees. 
According to him, “Under Clause 5 (ii) of our MOU, the association is under obligation to pay us our fees upon filing of their cases or entering of defence for them as the case may be. 
“We have fulfilled that requirement and had written series of demand letters to the Association notifying them of our intention to file action against them, but the association has neither replied any of our letters nor deemed it proper to even communicate us in any manner. 
“We even wrote a formal complaint to Nigerian Medical Association (NMA) as the umbrella body of Doctors in Nigeria over the same issue. The last communication we had from our clients, National Association of Resident Doctors was during the regime of their immediate past exco, the current excos are either indifferent to our course or they have just chosen in their wisdom or lack of it to ignore our demands in a most despicable manner.” 

The said Lawyer who recounted his efforts and sacrifices to the success and peace the association is enjoying today in so many areas stated that the association has been very unfair and inconsiderate to him and his legal team by abdicating their financial obligation to them. 
“It is unprofessional for us to beg for our legal fees,” he said, adding “the ethics of our profession forbid it, that is why we always reach a fee agreement with clients from the onset, and agreement are meant to be obeyed.” 
The lawyer said he doesn’t care if the Association debriefed him or not as his fees were well secured under the MOU. 
He stated that because of his fiduciary relationship with the association, he didn’t yet want to file any claim for damages against the Association for now but warned that “if the association continues to delay in making good their payment to them before the end of this month, they shall in addition to this suit, file a claim of N100, 000,000 general and exemplary damages against the Association.” 
When contacted, the first NARD President, Chinaka denied knowledge of the suit, even as he declined to make further comments until he was served. 
On his part, his predecessor, Onyebueze said he was aware of the suit, explaining that before he handed over, he had put a payment plan on ground for the settlement of the legal fees. 
The court is yet to fix date for the hearing of the matter.

posts.text:
Clive said: ↑ I grew up on a dairy farm - my dad had about 100 cows / followers and we employees 5 men and made a living from it - this was “just” 20 years ago
How many men does it take to look after 100 cows today using all the latest tech available ?
Don’t tell me dairy farming can’t be (and hasn’t already) mechanised and people replaced ! Click to expand... There are far too few people employed on many livestock farms these days working far too long for their welfare and for the best animal welfare. The margins are so small compared with the necessary labour cost that labour has been cut to below the minimum necessary on too many livestock farms. I see overworked tired people that struggle to pay their bills and who can’t afford the time or cost of having a life outside and away from their livestock all too often.
People, for instance, that just can’t afford a couple of days off to go to a trade show, either in time or money.
Something has to change from here. It is ‘unsustainable’ as it is in the long term. As many have said, no youngster with any ability and ambition and a sound head would wish to run their life in a dead end business like farming in a time of plenty.

posts.text:
WHY?
This is what the world need to ask itself.
Automate everything and then invent something for people to do to keep themselves physically and mentally healthy?
Listening to talk of banning plastics yesterday, it seems possible that after plastics made products cheaper and easier to move around the world people may get the idea of using reusable glass bottles for milk or a reusable wooden crate for fruit and veg.
In answer to the OP, you need to see that the majority of farm labour has come from families that have sold farms. There are less farmers to sell now and fewer ex farmers to be employed. All the large farms near here and finding it increasingly difficult to get staff which was hidden by a foreign supply of labour which is now diminishing. Very few who have enjoyed working outside of agriculture want to put up with the general sh!t involved in going back.
Just imagine trying to get one of the dragons den to invest in the average farm I need millions in assets, £100k's in machinery/ livestock and I'll work all hours for a negligible return. The question isn't why don't the young want to farm, but why the fudge do we?
